<p>&#8220;I should have presented my topic using the p4c [philosophy for children] method,&#8221; said a philosopher about about his talk at a conference on Plato&#8217;s theory of forms, after taking part in a demonstration of it.<span id="more-55816"></span></p>
<p>That remark is conveyed in the following guest post by <a href="https://www.lynn.edu/campus-directory/people/sophia-stone">Sophia Stone</a>, associate professor of philosophy at Lynn University, and founder and president of <a href="https://www.wisdoms-edgefoundation.org/">Wisdom’s Edge Foundation, Inc.</a>, a not-for-profit organization that gives free or reduced cost philosophy classes to communities that do not have access to the university. Some of the communities she serves are women in transition from homelessness or incarceration, the elderly in assisted living, the general public, and of course, children.</p>
<p>By the way, today is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GivingTuesday" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Giving Tuesday</a>. You can donate to Wisdom&#8217;s Edge <a href="https://www.instagram.com/linking/fundraiser?fundraiser_id=1355605119599257&amp;source_name=SHARE_LINK_Q_qPBQGbR6MjsKcYIGehQ1bCzx7tFWaViUR6G10J0OM39jkwC8GnAZgW2mg">here</a> (or <a href="https://www.wisdoms-edgefoundation.org/donate--fundraisers.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a>).</p>
